La Vuelta Femenina 2024

Marianne Vos won the 3rd stage of the Vuelta Femenina, while Blank Vas retained the red jersey. The next stage is expected to boil down to a bunch sprint before the first of three mountain finishes happens on Thursday. Stages 6 and 8 also finish uphill, while stage 7 is flat with a punchy hill in the finale.
Read more »

Vuelta Femenina 2024: Vos sprints to victory, Vas still leader

The 3rd stage of La Vuelta Femenina takes in almost 2,300 metres of climbing, still the race culminates in a bunch sprint. Marianne Vos powers to triumph, while Blanka Vas keeps the red jersey, although Vos is now only 1 second behind.
Read more »

Vuelta Femenina 2024 Route stage 3: Lucena – Teruel

Tuesday 30 April - The route undulates throughout the day in the race from Lucena to Teruel. Amounting to 131 kilometres, the elevation gain of the 3rd stage of the Vuelta for women takes in an elevation gain of 2,285 metres.
Read more »

Vuelta Femenina 2024 Route stage 4: Molina de Aragón – Zaragoza

Wednesday 1 May - The longest stage of La Vuelta Femenina spans 142 kilometres. The race from Molina de Aragón to Zaragoza is perfect for a bunch sprint.
Read more »

Vuelta Femenina 2024: The Route

The Vuelta Femenina is set to finish on Sunday with a mountain top finish in Madrid's ski station Valdesquí. Hilly races, chances for sprinters and two more mountain top finishes round out the route.
Read more »

Vuelta Femenina 2024: Riders

Last year's Vuelta Femenina boiled down to an intriguing battle between Annemiek van Vleuten and Demi Vollering. While the former has since retired, the latter is eager to secure her first victory in 2024 following her dominant campaign in 2023. Cyclingstage.com brings you the start list for La Vuelta Femenina.
Read more »

Giro 2024: The Route

The Giro d'Italia starts on Saturday 4 May in Turin and is set to finish on Sunday the 26th in Rome. Two summit finishes appear in the first week, while most climbing is done in the final week of action.
Read more »
